Mutinous soldiers in Ivory Coast opened access to the West African nation&#8217;s second city, Bouake, a leader of the uprising said on Sunday, as popular opposition to the nationwide revolt gained momentum.&#8220;We have decided to open the corridors to allow the population to do their work. We have nothing against the population,&#8221; Sergeant Seydou Kone told Reuters. Witnesses and a local lawmaker confirmed that traffic was circulating.-Reuters 